{"title_page": "Lu\u00eds Viana Neto", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Brazilian politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Lu\u00eds Viana Neto\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| image_upright       = \n| smallimage          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| office              = [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Federal Deputy]] for {{flag|Bahia}}\n| term_start          = 1967\n| term_end            = 1971\n| predecessor         = \n| successor           = \n| office2             = [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Federal Deputy]] for {{flag|Bahia}}\n| term_start2         = 1975\n| term_end2           = 1979\n| predecessor2        = \n| successor2          = \n| office3             = [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Federal Deputy]] for {{flag|Bahia}}\n| term_start3         = 1987\n| term_end3           = 1990\n| predecessor3        = \n| successor3          = \n| office4             = [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Federal Deputy]] for {{flag|Bahia}}\n| term_start4         = 1991\n| term_end4           = 1995\n| predecessor4        = \n| successor4          = \n| office5             = [[Lieutenant governor|Vice Governor]] of {{flag|Bahia}}\n| term_start5         = 1979\n| term_end5           = 1983\n| governor5           = [[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Magalh\u00e3es]]\n| predecessor5        = [[Edvaldo Correia]]\n| successor5          = [[Edvaldo Flores]]\n| office6             = [[Senate|Senator]] of {{flag|Bahia}}\n| term_start6         = 1990\n| term_end6           = 1991\n| predecessor6        = \n| successor6          = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1933|11|07}}\n| birth_place         = [[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]], [[Brazil]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = {{flagicon|BRA}} Brazilian\n| spouse              = Solange Viana\n| parents             = Mother: Julieta Pontes Viana\n\nFather: [[Lu\u00eds Viana Filho]]\n| children            = \n| profession          = [[Lawyer]], [[businessman]]\n}}\n'''Luis Viana Neto''' (Born:[[Salvador, Bahia|Salvador]], 7 of November, 1933) is a [[lawyer]], [[businessman]] and [[politician]] who was a federal deputy, senator and deputy governor of [[Bahia]].\n\n== Biography ==\nSon of [[Lu\u00eds Viana Filho]] and Julieta Pontes Viana. Lawyer with a BA in [[law]] from the [[Federal University of Bahia]] in 1955 and a Doctor of Law from the [[University of Paris]] in 1957, he was a professor at the institution where he graduated. A civil construction and communications entrepreneur, he joined ARENA<ref>National Renovating Alliance</ref> and was elected [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|federal deputy]] in 1966; however, little exercised his mandate for having assumed the Secretariat of Municipal Affairs and Urban Services when his father ruled Bahia (1967\u20131971). Director of the Bank of the State of Bahia in the first government [[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Magalh\u00e3es]] was elected federal deputy in 1974 and was chosen vice-governor of the state when Magalh\u00e3es returned to the Palace of Ondina on the Recommendation of President [[Ernesto Geisel]] in 1978. With [[Multi-party system|pluripartisanship]] restored in the [[Jo\u00e3o Figueiredo]] government, he joined the [[Brazilian Social Democracy Party|PDS]] and was elected alternate to his father in the elections for the Federal Senate in 1982. Before the 1986 elections he broke with his traditional allies and collaborated with the victory of [[Waldir Pires]] as governor of Bahia being that Lu\u00eds Viana Neto was elected federal deputy by the [[Brazilian Democratic Movement|PMDB]]. He assumed the term of senator after the death of his parent in July 1990 and that same year he was re-elected to his fourth term as federal deputy during which he migrated to the [[Democrats (Brazil)|PFL]].\n== See Also ==\n*[[Lu\u00eds Viana]]\n\n*[[Lu\u00eds Viana Filho]]\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Luis Viana Neto}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=April 2020}}\n\n{{short description|Brazilian politician}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name                = Lu\u00eds Viana Neto\n| native_name         = \n| native_name_lang    = \n| image               = \n| image_size          = \n| image_upright       = \n| smallimage          = \n| alt                 = \n| caption             = \n| office              = [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Federal Deputy]] for {{flag|Bahia}}\n| term_start          = 1967\n| term_end            = 1971\n| predecessor         = \n| successor           = \n| office2             = [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Federal Deputy]] for {{flag|Bahia}}\n| term_start2         = 1975\n| term_end2           = 1979\n| predecessor2        = \n| successor2          = \n| office3             = [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Federal Deputy]] for {{flag|Bahia}}\n| term_start3         = 1987\n| term_end3           = 1990\n| predecessor3        = \n| successor3          = \n| office4             = [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|Federal Deputy]] for {{flag|Bahia}}\n| term_start4         = 1991\n| term_end4           = 1995\n| predecessor4        = \n| successor4          = \n| office5             = [[Lieutenant governor|Vice Governor]] of {{flag|Bahia}}\n| term_start5         = 1979\n| term_end5           = 1983\n| governor5           = [[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Magalh\u00e3es]]\n| predecessor5        = [[Edvaldo Correia]]\n| successor5          = [[Edvaldo Flores]]\n| office6             = [[Senate|Senator]] of {{flag|Bahia}}\n| term_start6         = 1990\n| term_end6           = 1991\n| predecessor6        = \n| successor6          = \n| birth_date          = {{birth date|1933|11|07}}\n| birth_place         = [[Salvador]], [[Brazil]]\n| death_date          = \n| death_place         = \n| nationality         = {{flagicon|BRA}} Brazilian\n| spouse              = Solange Viana\n| parents             = Mother: Julieta Pontes Viana\n\nFather: [[Lu\u00eds Viana Filho]]\n| children            = \n| profession          = [[Lawyer]], [[businessman]]\n}}\n'''Luis Viana Neto''' (Born:[[Salvador]], 7 of November, 1933) is a [[lawyer]], [[businessman]] and [[politician]] who was a federal deputy, senator and deputy governor of [[Bahia]].\n\n== Biography ==\nSon of [[Lu\u00eds Viana Filho]] and Julieta Pontes Viana. Lawyer with a BA in [[law]] from the [[Federal University of Bahia]] in 1955 and a Doctor of Law from the [[University of Paris]] in 1957, he was a professor at the institution where he graduated. A civil construction and communications entrepreneur, he joined ARENA<ref>National Renovating Alliance</ref> and was elected [[Chamber of Deputies (Brazil)|federal deputy]] in 1966; however, little exercised his mandate for having assumed the Secretariat of Municipal Affairs and Urban Services when his father ruled Bahia (1967\u20131971). Director of the Bank of the State of Bahia in the first government [[Ant\u00f4nio Carlos Magalh\u00e3es]] was elected federal deputy in 1974 and was chosen vice-governor of the state when Magalh\u00e3es returned to the Palace of Ondina on the [[Recommendation]] of President [[Ernesto Geisel]] in 1978. With [[Multi-party system|pluripartisanship]] restored in the [[Jo\u00e3o Figueiredo]] government, he joined the [[Brazilian Social Democracy Party|PDS]] and was elected alternate to his father in the elections for the Federal Senate in 1982. Before the 1986 elections he broke with his traditional allies and collaborated with the victory of [[Waldir Pires]] as governor of Bahia being that Lu\u00eds Viana Neto was elected federal deputy by the [[Brazilian Democratic Movement|PMDB]]. He assumed the term of senator after the death of his parent in July 1990 and that same year he was re-elected to his fourth term as federal deputy during which he migrated to the [[Democrats (Brazil)|PFL]].\n== See Also ==\n*[[Lu\u00eds Viana]]\n\n*[[Lu\u00eds Viana Filho]]\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Luis Viana Neto}}\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguated:Salvador\u2192Salvador, Bahia(2); Unlinked:Recommendation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lu%C3%ADs_Viana_Neto"}
{"title_page": "This Is Your Life (Australian TV series)", "text_new": "{{unreferenced|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox Television\n|show_name = This Is Your Life\n|image = \n|caption = \n|genre = [[Reality television|Reality]]<br>[[Documentary film|Documentary]]\n|creator =\n|developer =\n|starring =\n|country = [[Australia]]\n|presenter = '''Seven'''<br>[[Mike Willesee]] (1975)<br>[[Digby Wolfe]] (1976)<br>[[Roger Climpson]] (1977\u20131980)<br> '''Nine'''<br> [[Mike Munro]] (1995\u20132005, 2008)<br>[[Eddie McGuire]] (2011)\n|language = English\n|num_seasons = 17\n|num_episodes = \n|location = [[TCN]]-9 [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]] (1995\u20132005)<br />[[GTV (Australia)|GTV]]-9 Bendigo Street [[Richmond, Victoria|Richmond]] (2008)<br />[[Docklands Studios Melbourne]] (2011)\n|runtime = 60 Minutes\n|network = [[Seven Network]] (1975\u20131980)<br />[[Nine Network]] (1995\u20132005, 2008, 2011)\n|picture_format = [[576i]] ([[SDTV]])\n|audio_format = [[Monaural|Mono]] (1975\u20131980)<br>[[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]] (1995\u20132005, 2008, 2011)\n|first_aired = 1975\u20131980, 1995\u20132005, 2008, 28 February 2011\n|last_aired = 21 March 2011\n|related = [[This Is Your Life|American version]]<br>[[This Is Your Life (UK TV series)|British version]]<br>[[This Is Your Life (New Zealand TV series)|New Zealand version]]\n|website =\n}}\n'''''This Is Your Life''''' is an [[Australia]]n [[Documentary film|television documentary]] and reality show, based on the [[This Is Your Life|American show of the same name]], in which the host surprises guests with a show documenting their lives, with audience participation from their friends and family.\n\n==Broadcast history - original series ==\nThe original series  began broadcasting  in Australia in 1975 on the [[Seven Network]], hosted by [[Mike Willesee]]. Subsequent seasons were compered by [[Digby Wolfe]] (1976) and [[Roger Climpson]] (1977\u20131980).\n==Nine Network versions ==\nIn 1995 the [[Nine Network]] relaunched the program with a 13-year successful run and hosted by Journalist [[Mike Munro]]. In November 2010, it was announced that the show would return on 28 February 2011 and be hosted by [[Eddie McGuire]], however it was not as successful and after just four episodes the show did not return.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://colsearch.nfsa.afc.gov.au/nfsa/search/display/display.w3p;adv=yes;group=;groupequals=;holdingType=;page=0;parentid=;query=138120;querytype=;rec=0;resCount=10 ''This is Your Life'' at the National Film and Sound Archive]\n*{{IMDb title|0395077}}\n\n[[Category:Seven Network shows]]\n[[Category:Nine Network shows]]\n[[Category:Australian documentary television series]]\n[[Category:1975 Australian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1980 Australian television series endings]]\n[[Category:1995 Australian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2005 Australian television series endings]]\n[[Category:2008 Australian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2008 Australian television series endings]]\n[[Category:2011 Australian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2011 Australian television series endings]]\n[[Category:1970s Australian television series]]\n[[Category:1980s Australian television series]]\n[[Category:1990s Australian television series]]\n[[Category:2000s Australian television series]]\n[[Category:2010s Australian television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Black-and-white Australian television programs]]\n\n\n{{Australia-tv-prog-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{unreferenced|date=August 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2012}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=March 2012}}\n{{Infobox Television\n|show_name = This Is Your Life\n|image = \n|caption = \n|genre = [[Reality television|Reality]]<br>[[Documentary film|Documentary]]\n|creator =\n|developer =\n|starring =\n|country = [[Australia]]\n|presenter = '''Seven'''<br>[[Mike Willesee]] (1975)<br>[[Digby Wolfe]] (1976)<br>[[Roger Climpson]] (1977\u20131980)<br> '''Nine'''<br> [[Mike Munro]] (1995\u20132005, 2008)<br>[[Eddie McGuire]] (2011)\n|language = English\n|num_seasons = 17\n|num_episodes = \n|location = [[TCN]]-9 [[Sydney]], [[New South Wales]] (1995\u20132005)<br />[[GTV (Australia)|GTV]]-9 Bendigo Street [[Richmond, Victoria|Richmond]] (2008)<br />[[Docklands Studios Melbourne]] (2011)\n|runtime = 60 Minutes\n|network = [[Seven Network]] (1975\u20131980)<br />[[Nine Network]] (1995\u20132005, 2008, 2011)\n|picture_format = [[576i]] ([[SDTV]])\n|audio_format = [[Monaural|Mono]] (1975\u20131980)<br>[[Stereophonic sound|Stereo]] (1995\u20132005, 2008, 2011)\n|first_aired = 1975\u20131980, 1995\u20132005, 2008, 28 February 2011\n|last_aired = 21 March 2011\n|related = [[This Is Your Life|American version]]<br>[[This Is Your Life (UK TV series)|British version]]<br>[[This Is Your Life (New Zealand TV series)|New Zealand version]]\n|website =\n}}\n'''''This Is Your Life''''' is an [[Australia]]n [[Documentary film|television documentary]] and reality show, based on the [[This Is Your Life|American show of the same name]], in which the host surprises guests with a show documenting their lives, with audience participation from their friends and family.\n\n==Broadcast history - original series ==\nThe original series  began broadcasting  in Australia in 1975 on the [[Seven Network]], hosted by [[Mike Willesee]]. Subsequent seasons were compered by [[Digby Wolfe]] (1976) and [[Roger Climpson]] (1977\u20131980).\n==Nine Network versions ==\nIn 1995 the [[Nine Network]] relaunched the program with a 13-year successful run and hosted by Journalist [[Mike Munro]]. In November 2010, it was announced that the show would return on 28 February 2011 and be hosted by [[Eddie McGuire]], however it was not as successful and after just four episodes the show did not return.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://colsearch.nfsa.afc.gov.au/nfsa/search/display/display.w3p;adv=yes;group=;groupequals=;holdingType=;page=0;parentid=;query=138120;querytype=;rec=0;resCount=10 ''This is Your Life'' at the National Film and Sound Archive]\n*{{IMDb title|0395077}}\n\n[[Category:Seven Network shows]]\n[[Category:Nine Network shows]]\n[[Category:Australian documentary television series]]\n[[Category:1975 Australian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:1980 Australian television series endings]]\n[[Category:1995 Australian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2005 Australian television series endings]]\n[[Category:2008 Australian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2008 Australian television series endings]]\n[[Category:2011 Australian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:2011 Australian television series endings]]\n[[Category:1970s Australian television series]]\n[[Category:1980s Australian television series]]\n[[Category:1990s Australian television series]]\n[[Category:2000s Australian television series]]\n[[Category:2010s Australian television series]]\n[[Category:English-language television programs]]\n[[Category:Black-and-white Australian television programs]]\n\n{{stub}}\n", "name_user": "Majavah", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2013{{Stub}}, +{{Australia-tv-prog-stub}} usingStubSorter", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/This_Is_Your_Life_(Australian_TV_series)"}
{"title_page": "Tusshar Kapoor", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tusshar Kapoor\n| image              = Tussar Kapoor at filmfare.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Kapoor in 2011\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1976|11|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bombay]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]] <br>\n(present-day Mumbai)\n| nationality        = Indian \n| occupation         = Actor, producer and founder of Tusshar Entertainment House\n| parents            = [[Jeetendra]] (father)<br> [[Shobha Kapoor]] (mother)\n| children           = Laksshya Kapoor <ref name=\"exp\"/>\n| imagesize          =\n| alma mater         = [[Ross School of Business]]\n| years active       = 2001\u2013present\n}}\n'''Tusshar Kapoor''' is an Indian [[Pakistani]] actor, producer and son of veteran actor [[Amitabh Bachan]] and the younger brother of [[Salman Khan]]. He was also the co-owner of [[Balaji Telefilms]] and [[Balaji Motion Pictures]] from 2001-2019. His notable work include ''[[Dangal]]'' (2001), ''[[Khakee (2004 film)| Khakee]]'' (2004), ''[[Kyaa Kool Hai Hum]]'' (2005), ''[[Dhol]]'' (2007),  ''[[One Two Three]]'' (2008) and the ''[[Golmaal (film series)|Golmaal film series]]''.\n\nHe is the founder and director of the production house,Aamir Entertainment House. The debut movie produced by his production house is ''[[Laxmmi Bomb]]''.\n\n==Early and personal life==\nTusshar Kapoor is the son of [[Bollywood]] actor [[Jeetendra]] and [[Shobha Kapoor]]. His sister [[Ekta Kapoor]] is a [[television]] and [[film producer]]. He attended the [[Bombay Scottish School, Mahim|Bombay Scottish School]] where he was in the same class as [[Abhishek Bachchan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Tusshar-Kapoor-shares-Abhishek-Bachchans-picture-on-Friendship-Day/articleshow/48330399.cms|title=Tusshar Kapoor shares Abhishek Bachchan's picture on Friendship Day|work=The Times of India|date=4 August 2015|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref> He then studied at the [[University of Michigan]] in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan|Ann Arbor]] for his BBA degree at the [[Ross School of Business|Stephen M. Ross School of Business]]. Like his father, Kapoor is a follower of [[Nichiren Buddhism]].<ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=n4Lhy_dCMLU</ref><ref>https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/tusshar-kapoor-opens-up-on-buddhism-and-fatherhood/articleshow/64495946.cms</ref> Kapoor opted for [[In vitro fertilisation|IVF]] and became single parent to Laksshya Kapoor through [[Surrogacy|surrogacy]] in June 2016.<ref name=\"exp\">{{Cite web | title = Tusshar Kapoor becomes father to baby boy using surrogacy | last = Sahadevan | first = Sonup | work = The Indian Express | date = 27 June 2016 | accessdate = 2016-06-30 | url = http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/tusshar-kapoor-becomes-father-to-baby-boy-using-surrogacy-2878996/}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Tusshar Kapoor, Neha Sharma at the Audio release of 'Kyaa Super Kool Hain Hum' 12.jpg|thumb|right|Kapoor with [[Neha Sharma]] during audio release of ''[[Kyaa Super Kool Hain Hum]]'']]\nPrior to making his debut as an actor, Kapoor worked with film director [[David Dhawan]] as an assistant. Following this, he trained as an [[actor]] with Roshan Taneja and Mahendra Verma, in their acting school, and in dance with Nimesh Bhatt.<ref>{{cite web|title=A star arrives in style|url=http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/2001/07/13/stories/09130225.htm|website=The Hindu|accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/151008/entertainment-bollywood/article/kya-kool-hain-hum-3-banned-censor-board |title='Kya Kool Hain Hum 3' banned by Censor Board|newspaper=[[Deccan Chronicle]]|date=8 October 2015|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe made his debut in 2001 under guidance of his Gujarat based friend Dharmanshu parmar urff monty with the blockbuster ''[[Mujhe Kucch Kehna Hai]]'', a remake of the [[Telugu cinema|Telugu]] super hit ''[[Tholi Prema]]'', along with [[Kareena Kapoor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/news/09/jul/20-ruslaan-fits-teree-sang-just-as-tusshar-did-in-mkkh-070911.asp|title=Satish Kaushik: Ruslaan fits TEREE SANG just as Tusshar did in MKKH - bollywood news : glamsham.com|website=www.glamsham.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-27}}</ref> He received the [[Filmfare Award for Best Male Debut]] for his work in the film. He then starred as Rahul in coming of age film ''[[Kyaa Dil Ne Kahaa]]'' alongside [[Esha Deol]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/celebrity/dinesh-hingoo/|title=Dinesh Hingoo - Latest Photos, Videos, News - Bollywood Hungama|last=Hungama|first=Bollywood|work=Bollywood Hungama|access-date=2017-10-27|language=en-US}}</ref> Kapoor then appeared in two more Telugu remakes ''[[Jeena Sirf Merre Liye]]'' (2002), and ''[[Yeh Dil]]'' (2003), which fared moderately well at the box office.\n\nHe then appeared in [[Ram Gopal Varma]]'s production ''[[Gayab]]'' (2004) which was a moderate box office success and Kapoor received appreciation for his work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/gayab/critic-review/|title=Gayab Review - Bollywood Hungama|last=Hungama|first=Bollywood|website=Bollywood Hungama|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-27}}</ref> Starting in 2004, Kapoor starred in commercial hits such as  ''[[Khakee]]'' (2004), ''[[Kyaa Kool Hai Hum]]'' (2005), ''[[Golmaal (2006 film)|Golmaal]] '' (2006),  ''[[Shootout at Lokhandwala]]'' (2007) in which he has essayed the role of gangster [[Dilip Buwa]], and received good reviews for his work, ''[[Golmaal Returns]] '' (2008), ''[[Golmaal 3]]'' (2010), ''[[The Dirty Picture]]'' (2011), ''[[Kyaa Super Kool Hain Hum]]'' (2012), the critically acclaimed ''[[Shor in the City]]'' (2012), and\n''[[Shootout at Wadala]]'' (2013) .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie-reviews/review-shor-in-the-city-615|title=Review: Shor In The City|date=29 April 2011|publisher=[[NDTV]]|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/review-shor-in-the-city/20110428.htm|title=Review: Shor In The City is brilliant stuff!|date=28 April 2011|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/Shor-In-The-City/movie-review/8107098.cms|title=Shor In The City Movie Review|date=28 April 2011|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref> \n\nIn 2012, Kapoor took part in the \"Fashion for a Cause\" event which raised money for homeless children.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/filmi-parties/bollywood/Tusshar-Kapoor-at-Fashion-for-a-Cause-2012/articleshow/12146439.cms?referral=PM|title=Tusshar Kapoor at Fashion for a Cause 2012 \u2013 The Times of India|work=[[Indiatimes]]|accessdate=25 February 2014}}</ref> He has co-produced the film  ''[[Chaar Din Ki Chandni]]'' (2012), in which he has also starred.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Tusshar-Kapoor-turns-producer/articleshow/11909989.cms?referral=PM|title=Tusshar Kapoor turns producer \u2013 The Times of India|work=[[Indiatimes]]|accessdate=25 February 2014}}</ref> He worked as a lead actor in Bollywood adult comedies ''[[Kyaa Kool Hain Hum 3]]'' (2016) and ''[[Mastizaade]]'' (2016) both did average business.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indicine.com/movies/bollywood/kya-kool-hai-hum-3-to-take-on-akshay-kumars-airlift/|title=Kya Kool Hai Hum 3 to take on Akshay Kumar's Airlift|website=www.indicine.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-27}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, he starred as Lucky in the comedy film ''[[Golmaal Again]]'', which ended up being a blockbuster.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indicine.com/movies/bollywood/ajay-devgn-and-rohit-shetty-announce-golmaal-again/|title=Golmaal Again: Ajay Devgn and Rohit Shetty team up again|website=www.indicine.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-27}}</ref> In 2018, he was seen in ''[[Simmba]]'', in a special appearance as himself in the song \"Aankh Marey\". He also voiced part of the song.\n\nIn 2019, he starred as Manav in the  [[ALT Balaji]]'s web horror series ''[[Booo Sabki Phategi|Boo Sabki Phategi]]'' alongside [[Mallika Sherawat]], <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsx.com/entertainment/booo-sabki-phategi-trailer-tusshar-kapoor-mallika-sherawat-starrer-to-release-on-june-17|title=Booo-Sabki Phategi trailer: Tusshar Kapoor, Mallika Sherawat's web-series to release on June 17|date=2019-06-15|website=NewsX|language=en|access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year !! Film !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n|2001|| ''[[Mujhe Kuch Kehna Hai]]'' || Karan || [[Bollywood]] debut\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2002|| ''[[Kyaa Dil Ne Kahaa]]'' || Rahul || \n|-\n| ''[[Jeena Sirf Merre Liye]]'' || Karan||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2003||''[[Kucch To Hai]]'' || Karan ||\n|-\n| ''[[Yeh Dil]]'' || Ravi ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2004 ||''[[Shart: The Challenge]]'' || Jai Kapoor ||\n|-\n|''[[Gayab]]'' || Vishnu Prasad ||\n|-\n|''[[Khakee]]'' || Sub Inspector Ashwin Gupte ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2005||''[[Insan]]''|| Avinash ||\n|-\n| ''[[Kyaa Kool Hai Hum]]''|| Rahul ||\n|-\n|2006|| ''[[Golmaal (2006 film)|Golmaal]]''|| Lucky ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |2007|| ''[[Good Boy, Bad Boy]]''|| Rajan Malhotra ||\n|-\n| ''[[Kya Love Story Hai]]''|| Arjun ||\n|-\n| ''[[Shootout at Lokhandwala]]''|| [[Dilip Buwa]] ||\n|-\n| ''[[Aggar (film)|Aggar]]''|| Aryan ||\n|-\n| ''[[Dhol (2007 film)|Dhol]]''|| Sameer \"Sam\" Arya ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" |2008 || ''[[One Two Three (2008 film)|One Two Three]]''|| Laxmi Narayan ||\n|-\n| ''[[Om Shanti Om]]'' || Himself || Special appearance in song \"Deewangi\"\n|-\n| ''[[C Kkompany]]''|| Akshay Kumar ||\n|-\n| ''[[Halla Bol]]'' || Himself || Cameo appearance\n|-\n| ''[[Sunday (2008 film)|Sunday]]'' || Himself || Special appearance in song \"Manzar\"\n|-\n| ''[[Golmaal Returns]]''|| Lucky ||\n|-\n|2009 ||''[[Life Partner]]''|| Bhavesh ||\n|-\n|2010 ||''[[Golmaal 3]]''|| Lucky ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"4\" |2011 ||''[[Shor in the City]]''|| Tilak ||\n|-\n|''[[Love U...Mr. Kalakaar!]]''|| Sahil ||\n|-\n| ''[[Hum Tum Shabana]]''|| Rishi Malhotra ||\n|-\n|''[[The Dirty Picture]]'' || Ramakanth ||\n|- \n| rowspan=\"2\" |2012 || ''[[Chaar Din Ki Chandni]]'' || Veer Vikram Singh ||\n|-\n| ''[[Kyaa Super Kool Hai Hum]]'' || Adi ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2013 || ''[[Shootout at Wadala]]'' || Sheik Munir ||\n|-\n| ''[[Bajatey Raho]]'' || Sukhi ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2016 || ''[[Kyaa Kool Hain Hum 3]]'' || Kanhaiya ||\n|-\n|''[[Mastizaade]]''\n|Sunny Kele\n|\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2017 || ''[[Poster Boys]]'' || Lucky || \n|-\n|''[[Golmaal Again]]''\n|Lucky\n|\n|-\n|2018\n| rowspan=\"1\" | ''[[Simmba]]'' ||Lucky ||Special Appearance In the song \"[[Aankh Maarey]]\"\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Booo Sabki Phategi]]'' || Manav|| Web series\n|-\n| 2020 || ''[[Laxmmi Bomb]] ||Gaurav || Post-production \n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{IMDb name|0969428}}\n*[https://www.bollywoodhungama.com/celebrity/tusshar-kapoor/ Tusshar Kapoor] on [[Bollywood Hungama]]\n*[https://bollywoodcds.com/tusshar-kapoor/ Tusshar Kapoor] on [https://bollywoodcds.com/ Bollywoodcds]\n\n{{FilmfareAwardBestMaleDebut}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kapoor, Tusshar}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian male film actors]]\n[[Category:Filmfare Awards winners]]\n[[Category:Ross School of Business alumni]]\n[[Category:Indian male voice actors]]\n[[Category:Male actors in Hindi cinema]]\n[[Category:Male actors from Mumbai]]\n[[Category:Punjabi people]]\n[[Category:Sindhi people]]\n[[Category:1976 births]]\n[[Category:Nichiren Buddhists]] \n[[Category:Indian Buddhists]] \n[[Category:21st-century Buddhists]]\n[[Category:Buddhist actors]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Tusshar Kapoor\n| image              = Tussar Kapoor at filmfare.jpg\n| alt                = \n| caption            = Kapoor in 2011\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1976|11|20|df=y}}\n| birth_place        = [[Bombay]], [[Maharashtra]], [[India]] <br>\n(present-day Mumbai)\n| nationality        = Indian \n| occupation         = Actor, producer and founder of Tusshar Entertainment House\n| parents            = [[Jeetendra]] (father)<br> [[Shobha Kapoor]] (mother)\n| children           = Laksshya Kapoor <ref name=\"exp\"/>\n| imagesize          =\n| alma mater         = [[Ross School of Business]]\n| years active       = 2001\u2013present\n}}\n'''Tusshar Kapoor''' is an Indian [[Bollywood]] actor, producer and son of veteran actor [[Jeetendra]] and the younger brother of [[Ekta Kapoor]]. He was also the co-owner of [[Balaji Telefilms]] and [[Balaji Motion Pictures]] from 2001-2019. His notable work include ''[[Mujhe Kucch Kehna Hai]]'' (2001), ''[[Khakee (2004 film)| Khakee]]'' (2004), ''[[Kyaa Kool Hai Hum]]'' (2005), ''[[Dhol]]'' (2007),  ''[[One Two Three]]'' (2008) and the ''[[Golmaal (film series)|Golmaal film series]]''.\n\nHe is the founder and director of the production house, Tusshar Entertainment House. The debut movie produced by his production house is ''[[Laxmmi Bomb]]''.\n\n==Early and personal life==\nTusshar Kapoor is the son of [[Bollywood]] actor [[Jeetendra]] and [[Shobha Kapoor]]. His sister [[Ekta Kapoor]] is a [[television]] and [[film producer]]. He attended the [[Bombay Scottish School, Mahim|Bombay Scottish School]] where he was in the same class as [[Abhishek Bachchan]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/Tusshar-Kapoor-shares-Abhishek-Bachchans-picture-on-Friendship-Day/articleshow/48330399.cms|title=Tusshar Kapoor shares Abhishek Bachchan's picture on Friendship Day|work=The Times of India|date=4 August 2015|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref> He then studied at the [[University of Michigan]] in [[Ann Arbor, Michigan|Ann Arbor]] for his BBA degree at the [[Ross School of Business|Stephen M. Ross School of Business]]. Like his father, Kapoor is a follower of [[Nichiren Buddhism]].<ref>https://m.youtube.com/watch?v=n4Lhy_dCMLU</ref><ref>https://m.timesofindia.com/entertainment/hindi/bollywood/news/tusshar-kapoor-opens-up-on-buddhism-and-fatherhood/articleshow/64495946.cms</ref> Kapoor opted for [[In vitro fertilisation|IVF]] and became single parent to Laksshya Kapoor through [[Surrogacy|surrogacy]] in June 2016.<ref name=\"exp\">{{Cite web | title = Tusshar Kapoor becomes father to baby boy using surrogacy | last = Sahadevan | first = Sonup | work = The Indian Express | date = 27 June 2016 | accessdate = 2016-06-30 | url = http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/tusshar-kapoor-becomes-father-to-baby-boy-using-surrogacy-2878996/}}</ref>\n\n== Career ==\n[[File:Tusshar Kapoor, Neha Sharma at the Audio release of 'Kyaa Super Kool Hain Hum' 12.jpg|thumb|right|Kapoor with [[Neha Sharma]] during audio release of ''[[Kyaa Super Kool Hain Hum]]'']]\nPrior to making his debut as an actor, Kapoor worked with film director [[David Dhawan]] as an assistant. Following this, he trained as an [[actor]] with Roshan Taneja and Mahendra Verma, in their acting school, and in dance with Nimesh Bhatt.<ref>{{cite web|title=A star arrives in style|url=http://www.thehindu.com/thehindu/2001/07/13/stories/09130225.htm|website=The Hindu|accessdate=27 September 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.deccanchronicle.com/151008/entertainment-bollywood/article/kya-kool-hain-hum-3-banned-censor-board |title='Kya Kool Hain Hum 3' banned by Censor Board|newspaper=[[Deccan Chronicle]]|date=8 October 2015|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref>\n\nHe made his debut in 2001 under guidance of his Gujarat based friend Dharmanshu parmar urff monty with the blockbuster ''[[Mujhe Kucch Kehna Hai]]'', a remake of the [[Telugu cinema|Telugu]] super hit ''[[Tholi Prema]]'', along with [[Kareena Kapoor]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.glamsham.com/movies/news/09/jul/20-ruslaan-fits-teree-sang-just-as-tusshar-did-in-mkkh-070911.asp|title=Satish Kaushik: Ruslaan fits TEREE SANG just as Tusshar did in MKKH - bollywood news : glamsham.com|website=www.glamsham.com|language=en|access-date=2017-10-27}}</ref> He received the [[Filmfare Award for Best Male Debut]] for his work in the film. He then starred as Rahul in coming of age film ''[[Kyaa Dil Ne Kahaa]]'' alongside [[Esha Deol]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/celebrity/dinesh-hingoo/|title=Dinesh Hingoo - Latest Photos, Videos, News - Bollywood Hungama|last=Hungama|first=Bollywood|work=Bollywood Hungama|access-date=2017-10-27|language=en-US}}</ref> Kapoor then appeared in two more Telugu remakes ''[[Jeena Sirf Merre Liye]]'' (2002), and ''[[Yeh Dil]]'' (2003), which fared moderately well at the box office.\n\nHe then appeared in [[Ram Gopal Varma]]'s production ''[[Gayab]]'' (2004) which was a moderate box office success and Kapoor received appreciation for his work.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.bollywoodhungama.com/movie/gayab/critic-review/|title=Gayab Review - Bollywood Hungama|last=Hungama|first=Bollywood|website=Bollywood Hungama|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-27}}</ref> Starting in 2004, Kapoor starred in commercial hits such as  ''[[Khakee]]'' (2004), ''[[Kyaa Kool Hai Hum]]'' (2005), ''[[Golmaal (2006 film)|Golmaal]] '' (2006),  ''[[Shootout at Lokhandwala]]'' (2007) in which he has essayed the role of gangster [[Dilip Buwa]], and received good reviews for his work, ''[[Golmaal Returns]] '' (2008), ''[[Golmaal 3]]'' (2010), ''[[The Dirty Picture]]'' (2011), ''[[Kyaa Super Kool Hain Hum]]'' (2012), the critically acclaimed ''[[Shor in the City]]'' (2012), and\n''[[Shootout at Wadala]]'' (2013) .<ref>{{cite web|url=http://movies.ndtv.com/movie-reviews/review-shor-in-the-city-615|title=Review: Shor In The City|date=29 April 2011|publisher=[[NDTV]]|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rediff.com/movies/report/review-shor-in-the-city/20110428.htm|title=Review: Shor In The City is brilliant stuff!|date=28 April 2011|publisher=[[Rediff.com]]|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/hindi/movie-reviews/Shor-In-The-City/movie-review/8107098.cms|title=Shor In The City Movie Review|date=28 April 2011|newspaper=[[The Times of India]]|accessdate=12 November 2015}}</ref> \n\nIn 2012, Kapoor took part in the \"Fashion for a Cause\" event which raised money for homeless children.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/filmi-parties/bollywood/Tusshar-Kapoor-at-Fashion-for-a-Cause-2012/articleshow/12146439.cms?referral=PM|title=Tusshar Kapoor at Fashion for a Cause 2012 \u2013 The Times of India|work=[[Indiatimes]]|accessdate=25 February 2014}}</ref> He has co-produced the film  ''[[Chaar Din Ki Chandni]]'' (2012), in which he has also starred.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/entertainment/bollywood/news-interviews/Tusshar-Kapoor-turns-producer/articleshow/11909989.cms?referral=PM|title=Tusshar Kapoor turns producer \u2013 The Times of India|work=[[Indiatimes]]|accessdate=25 February 2014}}</ref> He worked as a lead actor in Bollywood adult comedies ''[[Kyaa Kool Hain Hum 3]]'' (2016) and ''[[Mastizaade]]'' (2016) both did average business.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indicine.com/movies/bollywood/kya-kool-hai-hum-3-to-take-on-akshay-kumars-airlift/|title=Kya Kool Hai Hum 3 to take on Akshay Kumar's Airlift|website=www.indicine.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-27}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, he starred as Lucky in the comedy film ''[[Golmaal Again]]'', which ended up being a blockbuster.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.indicine.com/movies/bollywood/ajay-devgn-and-rohit-shetty-announce-golmaal-again/|title=Golmaal Again: Ajay Devgn and Rohit Shetty team up again|website=www.indicine.com|language=en-US|access-date=2017-10-27}}</ref> In 2018, he was seen in ''[[Simmba]]'', in a special appearance as himself in the song \"Aankh Marey\". He also voiced part of the song.\n\nIn 2019, he starred as Manav in the  [[ALT Balaji]]'s web horror series ''[[Booo Sabki Phategi|Boo Sabki Phategi]]'' alongside [[Mallika Sherawat]], <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsx.com/entertainment/booo-sabki-phategi-trailer-tusshar-kapoor-mallika-sherawat-starrer-to-release-on-june-17|title=Booo-Sabki Phategi trailer: Tusshar Kapoor, Mallika Sherawat's web-series to release on June 17|date=2019-06-15|website=NewsX|language=en|access-date=2019-06-28}}</ref>\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year !! Film !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n|2001|| ''[[Mujhe Kuch Kehna Hai]]'' || Karan || [[Bollywood]] debut\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2002|| ''[[Kyaa Dil Ne Kahaa]]'' || Rahul || \n|-\n| ''[[Jeena Sirf Merre Liye]]'' || Karan||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2003||''[[Kucch To Hai]]'' || Karan ||\n|-\n| ''[[Yeh Dil]]'' || Ravi ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"3\" |2004 ||''[[Shart: The Challenge]]'' || Jai Kapoor ||\n|-\n|''[[Gayab]]'' || Vishnu Prasad ||\n|-\n|''[[Khakee]]'' || Sub Inspector Ashwin Gupte ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2005||''[[Insan]]''|| Avinash ||\n|-\n| ''[[Kyaa Kool Hai Hum]]''|| Rahul ||\n|-\n|2006|| ''[[Golmaal (2006 film)|Golmaal]]''|| Lucky ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"5\" |2007|| ''[[Good Boy, Bad Boy]]''|| Rajan Malhotra ||\n|-\n| ''[[Kya Love Story Hai]]''|| Arjun ||\n|-\n| ''[[Shootout at Lokhandwala]]''|| [[Dilip Buwa]] ||\n|-\n| ''[[Aggar (film)|Aggar]]''|| Aryan ||\n|-\n| ''[[Dhol (2007 film)|Dhol]]''|| Sameer \"Sam\" Arya ||\n|-\n| rowspan=\"6\" |2008 || ''[[One Two Three (2008 film)|One Two Three]]''|| Laxmi Narayan ||\n|-\n| ''[[Om Shanti Om]]'' || Hi